description: From Latin intersecare (“to cut between, cut off”), from inter (“between”) + secare (“to cut”).

verbs.description: intersect (third-person singular simple present intersects, present participle intersecting, simple past and past participle intersected)

entries.meaning: (transitive, intransitive) To cut into or between; to cut or cross mutually; to divide into parts.
examples: Any two diameters of a circle intersect each other at the centre.

entries.meaning: (mathematics) Of two sets, to have at least one element in common.
